  "datePublished": "2026-02-27",
  "description": "Rhoticity, or the articulation of the r phoneme, has become a key feature of distinguishing General American English from other forms of English language.\nThe r phoneme is present in Proto-Indo-European and continued throughProto-Germanic. Then, it was likely a trill or tap, produced apically (with the tip of the tongue), and used in onset and coda positions, i.e. brōþēr, bearn.\nOld English (c. 500ce to 1100ce) maintained full rhoticity, but is indicated to halve evolved into an alveolar tap or trill.\n",
  "name": "Brief history of rhoticitiy in General American English",
